00:18:25.670 --> 00:18:26.670
Alright.

258
00:18:29.830 --> 00:18:32.000
Sorry if I overreacted in there.

259
00:18:32.020 --> 00:18:37.370
Just. uh. realizing I was wrong about
the only original idea I ever had.

260
00:18:37.610 --> 00:18:38.750
Yeah. what else did you learn?

261
00:18:39.510 --> 00:18:41.950
They give off infrared
light when they move.

262
00:18:41.970 --> 00:18:42.570
Mmm-mmm.

263
00:18:42.570 --> 00:18:45.410
Like so much. I don't know how
they store store all that energy.

264
00:18:45.440 --> 00:18:50.550
But their wavelength is exactly
the Petrova frequency.

265
00:18:50.790 --> 00:18:52.130
The light is how they move.

266
00:18:52.330 --> 00:18:56.330
Yeah. they consume the sun's energy.
and then they expel it for propulsion.

267
00:18:56.360 --> 00:18:57.970
They toot to scoot. basically.

268
00:19:00.170 --> 00:19:01.490
Why did it go to Venus?

269
00:19:03.770 --> 00:19:04.810
I don't know.

270
00:19:06.790 --> 00:19:09.190
- Okay. we'll tell you.
- What?

271
00:19:09.290 --> 00:19:13.450
I have 347 other biologists in 21
countries mobilizing as we speak.

272
00:19:13.470 --> 00:19:16.810
So thank you for your help.
I'm glad you didn't die.

273
00:19:16.810 --> 00:19:18.230
Let's pack this up!

274
00:19:22.610 --> 00:19:23.410
That's it?!

275
00:19:24.710 --> 00:19:25.170
That's it. Carl?

276
00:19:25.450 --> 00:19:26.030
Talk to her.

277
00:19:26.510 --> 00:19:27.690
You're taking all this stuff?

278
00:19:27.890 --> 00:19:31.190
At the school you said there were thousands
of people more qualified than you. so...

279
00:19:31.190 --> 00:19:32.070
I was being modest.

280
00:19:32.390 --> 00:19:33.370
I don't need modest.

281
00:19:33.400 --> 00:19:36.370
I need people who think they're right
when everyone else thinks they're wrong.

282
00:19:36.370 --> 00:19:38.110
I need people who
piss other people off.

283
00:19:38.110 --> 00:19:39.050
That's me!

284
00:19:39.330 --> 00:19:40.250
Do you want to
be on our project?

285
00:19:41.570 --> 00:19:42.870
If you...

286
00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:46.020
If you think
I can help. then...

287
00:19:46.050 --> 00:19:47.330
Just answer the question.

288
00:19:48.470 --> 00:19:50.410
I want to help the world.

289
00:19:50.510 --> 00:19:51.530
I left you three dots.

290
00:19:52.250 --> 00:19:53.290
Just three. huh?

291
00:19:53.510 --> 00:19:54.270
Plus the one you killed.

292
00:19:55.730 --> 00:19:56.650
I would take the three.

293
00:19:59.530 --> 00:20:00.990
- Yes?
- I'll-I'll take the dots.

294
00:20:01.390 --> 00:20:02.510
Get to work. Dr. Grace.

295
00:20:03.990 --> 00:20:06.750
The world is counting on you.

296
00:21:14.790 --> 00:21:15.230
<i>Hey. Carl?</i>

297
00:21:17.250 --> 00:21:17.950
<i>This is Carl.</i>

298
00:21:18.630 --> 00:21:22.610
<i>Imagine... for a second that
you're an interstellar microorganism.</i>

299
00:21:23.210 --> 00:21:23.990
<i>I'm not doing that.</i>

300
00:21:26.290 --> 00:21:28.030
<i>Why would you leave
the Sun and go to Venus?</i>

301
00:21:29.210 --> 00:21:31.830
<i>Why not stop at
Mercury. it's closer?</i>

302
00:21:33.350 --> 00:21:34.490
<i>Maybe fresh air?</i>

303
00:21:35.150 --> 00:21:36.830
<i>Venus's atmosphere
is mostly CO2.</i>

304
00:21:36.970 --> 00:21:38.510
<i>Maybe that's fresh air to them.</i>

305
00:21:38.650 --> 00:21:40.410
<i>You don't know what doing
a little space dust like?</i>

306
00:21:46.030 --> 00:21:46.770
<i>Hey. Carl?</i>

307
00:21:47.770 --> 00:21:49.190
<i>Do we have an expense account?</i>

308
00:21:49.420 --> 00:21:50.690
<i>We don't.</i>

309
00:21:55.770 --> 00:21:56.610
<i>But. I do.</i>

310
00:22:39.870 --> 00:22:41.070
Thank you.

311
00:22:41.110 --> 00:22:41.990
Do you have a coupon?

312
00:22:42.170 --> 00:22:43.810
We don't need a coupon.
We're the government.

313
00:22:44.210 --> 00:22:44.810
Which government?

314
00:22:45.490 --> 00:22:46.050
All of them.

315
00:22:48.730 --> 00:22:50.370
So this box is Venus?

316
00:22:50.510 --> 00:22:51.490
The box is Venus.

317
00:22:52.070 --> 00:22:55.690
It's set to emit the same infrared
light frequency as Venus's CO2 atmosphere.

318
00:22:56.070 --> 00:22:58.270
So if the dots move when
you turn the lights on.

319
00:22:58.570 --> 00:23:00.550
that means they're
looking for CO2.

320
00:23:00.690 --> 00:23:02.450
Thus proving the Carl Hypothesis.

321
00:23:03.430 --> 00:23:03.730
Sick.

322
00:23:08.190 --> 00:23:09.200
- All right.
- All right.

323
00:23:09.220 --> 00:23:10.230
You ready?

324
00:23:14.850 --> 00:23:15.210
Uh-oh.

325
00:23:16.530 --> 00:23:17.210
Why are you saying. uh-oh?

326
00:23:17.870 --> 00:23:19.630
The Astrophage
moved off the slide.

327
00:23:20.550 --> 00:23:20.750
Huh?

328
00:23:21.290 --> 00:23:22.130
We lost them.

329
00:23:22.910 --> 00:23:24.080
What do you mean we lost them?

330
00:23:24.110 --> 00:23:24.570
Go get them.

331
00:23:25.610 --> 00:23:26.940
If I open the door
in the light....

332
00:23:26.960 --> 00:23:28.920
they’re gonna escape.
and then we’ll lose them forever.

333
00:23:28.940 --> 00:23:30.190
At least now they're in the box.

334
00:23:30.550 --> 00:23:31.810
So we’ll just
turn the lights off.

335
00:23:31.910 --> 00:23:33.970
But there’ll still be light.
It’s gotta be total darkness.

336
00:23:33.970 --> 00:23:37.170
Okay. so just put
this box in another box.

337
00:23:58.150 --> 00:23:59.590
<i>Go ahead and close it. Over.</i>

338
00:24:00.590 --> 00:24:02.610
<i>I can hear you.</i>

339
00:24:08.030 --> 00:24:09.650
<i>Entering phase two.</i>

340
00:24:15.590 --> 00:24:16.410
<i>I'm in.</i>

341
00:24:22.770 --> 00:24:23.990
<i>Please report. Over.</i>

342
00:24:27.270 --> 00:24:27.950
<i>There's one.</i>

343
00:24:29.990 --> 00:24:31.150
<i>There's two!</i>

344
00:24:31.670 --> 00:24:33.170
<i>Come on. get the third one.</i>

345
00:24:35.810 --> 00:24:36.700
<i>Got sample three.</i>

346
00:24:36.720 --> 00:24:38.870
<i>The Three Musketeers.
The Three Stooges.</i>

347
00:24:42.990 --> 00:24:43.790
<i>Uh-oh.</i>

348
00:24:44.110 --> 00:24:44.990
<i>What?</i>

349
00:24:45.090 --> 00:24:45.970
<i>What?</i>

350
00:24:47.130 --> 00:24:48.330
<i>Are you sitting down?</i>

351
00:24:48.910 --> 00:24:50.690
<i>No. I'm standing
like a grown man.</i>

352
00:24:51.430 --> 00:24:52.210
<i>'Cause there's a fourth.</i>

353
00:24:53.990 --> 00:24:54.310
<i>What?</i>

354
00:24:56.950 --> 00:24:58.310
<i>We're fathers. Carl.</i>

355
00:25:01.530 --> 00:25:02.790
<i>Now I'm sitting down.</i>

356
00:25:06.890 --> 00:25:07.570
<i>Stratt.</i>

357
00:25:08.210 --> 00:25:09.110
Carl and I made a baby.

358
00:25:11.050 --> 00:25:11.730
<i>What?</i>

359
00:25:12.350 --> 00:25:14.230
We figured out how
Astrophage breeds.

360
00:25:14.710 --> 00:25:15.770
<i>Don't move.</i>

361
00:25:18.430 --> 00:25:19.230
Wheels up.

362
00:25:22.310 --> 00:25:25.040
You know. Carl. when Stratt
said she was sending a jet.

363
00:25:25.060 --> 00:25:26.790
I thought you meant like a PJ or something.

364
00:25:26.890 --> 00:25:27.550
I thought you did.

365
00:25:27.690 --> 00:25:27.950
I know that.

366
00:25:28.890 --> 00:25:29.690
Take this.

367
00:25:31.090 --> 00:25:34.430
It's been a long time since I've taken a pill
from a stranger without knowing what it was.

368
00:25:36.850 --> 00:25:37.840
Stop!

369
00:25:37.970 --> 00:25:38.950
Stop!

370
00:25:49.050 --> 00:25:50.990
Dr. Grace. how was your flight?

371
00:25:56.450 --> 00:25:57.330
Where are we?

372
00:25:57.330 --> 00:25:57.930
The ocean.

373
00:25:58.130 --> 00:26:00.350
The Astrophage reproduction.
can you do it at scale?

374
00:26:00.750 --> 00:26:02.050
Oh. in theory.

375
00:26:02.150 --> 00:26:04.840
Uh. you just get a bunch
of elbow-shaped pipe.

376
00:26:04.860 --> 00:26:06.170
put sunlight in one end...

377
00:26:06.210 --> 00:26:07.410
Excuse me for a second.

378
00:26:08.670 --> 00:26:09.490
Write it down.

379
00:26:09.510 --> 00:26:11.330
Yes. ma’am.

380
00:26:11.350 --> 00:26:13.590
...and IR line CO2 in the other.

381
00:26:14.670 --> 00:26:16.550
- Repeat.
- Anything else you need for this?

382
00:26:16.650 --> 00:26:16.870
Just some water.

383
00:26:16.990 --> 00:26:18.810
He gave me a pill
and it’s still in my throat.

384
00:26:19.210 --> 00:26:20.270
Two venti coffees?

385
00:26:20.450 --> 00:26:21.370
Thank you so much.

386
00:26:21.490 --> 00:26:22.030
Water for him.

387
00:26:22.030 --> 00:26:22.390
Or coffee. That's it.

388
00:26:23.310 --> 00:26:24.310
I need both.

389
00:26:24.590 --> 00:26:25.130
Or not.

390
00:26:25.630 --> 00:26:29.250
Okay. so this is kind of a tough room.
So don't take it personally.

391
00:26:29.250 --> 00:26:30.190
I don't need anything fancy.

392
00:26:30.410 --> 00:26:32.490
As long as there's a bed
and a shower. I'm good.

393
00:26:32.510 --> 00:26:34.010
So...

394
00:26:37.950 --> 00:26:38.990
I can't.

395
00:26:39.010 --> 00:26:40.470
- I can’t do this.
- Come on. Yes.

396
00:26:40.490 --> 00:26:41.450
- I can’t. I can’t.
- You’re doing great.

397
00:26:42.530 --> 00:26:45.670
Everyone. this is Dr. Ryland Grace
from the United States.

398
00:26:45.870 --> 00:26:46.850
Please go here.

399
00:26:46.910 --> 00:26:47.430
Thank you.

400
00:26:47.770 --> 00:26:50.610
And he figured out
how to breed Astrophage.

401
00:26:56.370 --> 00:26:57.610
How did you do it?

402
00:26:57.610 --> 00:26:59.470
How long does the process take?

403
00:26:59.790 --> 00:27:02.010
Was it reproduced by
mitosis or meiosis?

404
00:27:02.130 --> 00:27:03.350
<i>What is the incubation period?</i>

405
00:27:04.970 --> 00:27:06.770
Um...

406
00:27:08.230 --> 00:27:11.490
Carl and I made a mini Venus
out of a plywood box....

407
00:27:11.490 --> 00:27:16.310
and as soon as the samples recognized
the. uh. spectral signature of CO2.

408
00:27:16.310 --> 00:27:17.890
they were...

409
00:27:19.270 --> 00:27:20.910
They were like. “Whoomp! There it is!”

410
00:27:21.250 --> 00:27:22.730
- Okay.
- “Whoomp! There it is!”

411
00:27:22.730 --> 00:27:23.710
You can sit down
in this chair.

412
00:27:23.740 --> 00:27:24.310
Who’s Carl?

413
00:27:24.430 --> 00:27:27.130
While your experiment
was crude and clumsy.

414
00:27:27.170 --> 00:27:29.610
our scientists have
replicated his results.

415
00:27:32.050 --> 00:27:33.730
I'm sorry.
how did you see...?

416
00:27:33.750 --> 00:27:34.490
How did you...?

417
00:27:34.550 --> 00:27:37.570
We estimate an eight-day doubling
time under optimal conditions.

418
00:27:37.990 --> 00:27:39.050
Dr. Grace is right.

419
00:27:39.510 --> 00:27:41.490
- Oh.
- It is the CO2.

420
00:27:41.710 --> 00:27:42.870
That's why they're
going to Venus.

421
00:27:43.030 --> 00:27:44.350
Please say it for everyone.

422
00:27:44.370 --> 00:27:45.490
That's why they're
going to Venus.

423
00:27:45.870 --> 00:27:50.930
So that’s why they’re going to Venus.
is what Dr. Grace wants to say.

424
00:27:51.070 --> 00:27:51.970
They’re going to breed.

425
00:27:52.750 --> 00:27:54.210
Whoomp. there it is.

426
00:27:55.910 --> 00:27:57.710
I really like him.

427
00:27:58.010 --> 00:27:59.930
How long to make two
million kilograms?

428
00:28:00.370 --> 00:28:01.070
Two million?

429
00:28:03.430 --> 00:28:04.790
Two million is...

430
00:28:04.810 --> 00:28:10.330
Why... on Earth would you
need that much Astrophage?

431
00:28:10.390 --> 00:28:11.610
Nobody told him?

432
00:28:12.650 --> 00:28:14.530
He has no clearance.

433
00:28:14.530 --> 00:28:15.270
Please stand up. Dr. Grace.

434
00:28:15.870 --> 00:28:16.430
Clearance?

435
00:28:16.630 --> 00:28:17.370
Stand up.

436
00:28:18.870 --> 00:28:23.510
I hereby grant you top secret clearance to all
information pertaining to Project Hail Mary.

437
00:28:24.610 --> 00:28:25.730
What's Project Hail Mary?

438
00:28:28.270 --> 00:28:28.990
All right.

439
00:28:32.690 --> 00:28:34.570
The sun is not the
only star dying.

440
00:28:35.050 --> 00:28:37.350
There is a clear
pattern of infection.

441
00:28:37.450 --> 00:28:40.530
Every star was infected
by its neighbor except one.

442
00:28:41.350 --> 00:28:42.230
Tau Ceti?

443
00:28:42.250 --> 00:28:42.730
Tau Ceti.

444
00:28:42.750 --> 00:28:44.610
That's right. 11.9 light years away.

445
00:28:44.690 --> 00:28:47.950
It is uninfected despite being well
within the cluster of infected stars.

446
00:28:48.410 --> 00:28:48.850
Why?

447
00:28:49.330 --> 00:28:50.330
Why? Tell him.

448
00:28:50.590 --> 00:28:52.150
We don't know.

449
00:28:52.250 --> 00:28:56.190
Which is why we decided to build
a ship to go there and find out.

450
00:28:56.710 --> 00:28:58.050
It's 11.9 light years away.

451
00:28:58.090 --> 00:28:59.810
You can't just build
an interstellar ship.

452
00:29:00.270 --> 00:29:00.990
Oh. yeah. we can.

453
00:29:01.450 --> 00:29:02.990
The ship is not
really the problem.

454
00:29:03.530 --> 00:29:06.370
The energy required to power
the ship is the problem.

455
00:29:06.590 --> 00:29:07.850
It was the problem.

456
00:29:08.070 --> 00:29:08.810
Weep. weep.

457
00:29:10.010 --> 00:29:11.470
The Astrophage is the fuel.

458
00:29:11.750 --> 00:29:13.790
Provided we can
make enough of it.

459
00:29:13.790 --> 00:29:16.170
And for that. we
need you. my friend.

460
00:29:18.690 --> 00:29:19.250
Me?

461
00:29:20.270 --> 00:29:23.230
Ooh. Those little guys
store a lot of energy.

462
00:29:23.810 --> 00:29:26.190
One mistake in that much
Astrophage could vaporize...

463
00:29:26.970 --> 00:29:27.530
California.

464
00:29:27.970 --> 00:29:30.110
That’s true. which is why
you now live on a boat

465
00:29:30.110 --> 00:29:32.490
in the middle of the ocean
in case. "boom boom".

466
00:29:32.690 --> 00:29:33.830
I live on the boat?

467
00:29:34.010 --> 00:29:34.470
You do.

468
00:29:35.370 --> 00:29:37.370
So you wanna build
a near-light speed spaceship.

469
00:29:37.930 --> 00:29:40.350
have it travel further
than any human-made object

470
00:29:40.350 --> 00:29:44.650
has ever traveled.
and visit a star just to...

471
00:29:44.680 --> 00:29:45.850
“see what’s up”?

472
00:29:45.870 --> 00:29:46.230
Yeah.

473
00:29:46.810 --> 00:29:47.610
And then what?

474
00:29:47.710 --> 00:29:50.250
There won’t be enough
fuel for a round-trip.

475
00:29:50.310 --> 00:29:53.070
so they send their findings
back to Earth on probes.

476
00:29:56.150 --> 00:29:57.990
And. uh. the astronauts...

477
00:30:01.270 --> 00:30:02.490
die in space?

478
00:30:03.030 --> 00:30:03.610
Yes.

479
00:30:06.670 --> 00:30:07.350
Space.

480
00:30:11.050 --> 00:30:14.250
Any other plans
you’ve thought of?

481
00:30:14.250 --> 00:30:17.310
Anything else. any else
you’re kicking around?

482
00:30:17.510 --> 00:30:21.050
There are infinite possibilities
for this to go wrong.

483
00:30:21.080 --> 00:30:22.350
It almost certainly won’t work.

484
00:30:22.510 --> 00:30:25.190
It's what you Americans
would call a long shot.

485
00:30:25.770 --> 00:30:26.110
Hail Mary.

486
00:30:27.610 --> 00:30:28.890
I get it now.

487
00:30:29.410 --> 00:30:32.310
The alternative is
to just do nothing.

488
00:30:32.930 --> 00:30:35.290
And to starve and
to kill each other

489
00:30:35.290 --> 00:30:37.590
and watch everything on
this planet go extinct.

490
00:30:37.970 --> 00:30:38.570
including us.

491
00:30:39.870 --> 00:30:40.550
So...

492
00:31:01.270 --> 00:31:03.390
That's a long time
to be in space.

493
00:31:04.270 --> 00:31:06.010
We'll be in comas
for most of it.

494
00:31:06.350 --> 00:31:07.710
But is that even safe?

495
00:31:08.070 --> 00:31:09.390
Nothing about this is safe.

496
00:31:24.890 --> 00:31:25.870
<i>We only need three.</i>

497
00:31:26.890 --> 00:31:28.300
<i>A pilot.</i>

498
00:31:28.620 --> 00:31:30.050
<i>an engineer.</i>

499
00:31:30.470 --> 00:31:32.370
<i>and a scientist.</i>

500
00:31:36.590 --> 00:31:38.370
Commander Yao.

501
00:31:41.370 --> 00:31:43.770
I must have known you.
but I just don't remember.

502
00:31:44.870 --> 00:31:50.030
You make a funny face in
literally every picture.

503
00:31:51.550 --> 00:31:58.670
You must have been very
smart and strong and brave.

504
00:32:03.410 --> 00:32:05.410
Ilyukhina.

505
00:32:05.830 --> 00:32:08.110
First. I owe you
three bags of vodka.

506
00:32:09.670 --> 00:32:11.730
You seem to have
had a lot of friends.

507
00:32:12.810 --> 00:32:14.210
This picture of you.

508
00:32:14.230 --> 00:32:16.030
what looks like
sneaking into the Kremlin.

509
00:32:16.530 --> 00:32:17.190
is

510
00:32:19.590 --> 00:32:20.150
legendary.

511
00:32:22.490 --> 00:32:23.910
I wish you were still here.

512
00:32:25.990 --> 00:32:27.430
I wish I wasn't alone.

513
00:32:28.430 --> 00:32:32.170
I wish I was doing a better job.

514
00:32:32.170 --> 00:32:35.650
I just. uh...

515
00:32:37.910 --> 00:32:39.750
You were both very loved.

516
00:32:41.670 --> 00:32:43.630
You deserve much more than this.

517
00:32:46.030 --> 00:32:50.670
I'll do my best to make
sure that you don't...

518
00:32:51.350 --> 00:32:54.170
You know. that you didn't...

519
